Rob, you have a right to buy and own a car as long as you don’t operate it on public property (such as a highway). If you owned 100 acres in New Mexico, and had a race trak built, you could drive it all day and not need a drivers license or insurance, etc. However, if you want to operate that same vehicle on “public” tax paid for property, then the government has the wiggle room to step in and require a drivers license (proof of competency, or a certification if you will), and all the other stuff they throw on. Same way with firearms, you can own (in those states that are still part of the US) as many, and whatever type you want, BUT if you want to carry one in public, you need a “certification”, or license. While I don’t agree with this in principle, I do understand the need for it in some cases.<br>
