Being able to own a firearm was considered a “right” by those guys back in the 1700’s because as Mao said, “Political power flows from the barrel of a gun”. They wanted to construct a government where the political power came from the “people”. If the “people” could not be armed, or could be disarmed by that government, then they no longer had real power over the government. Firearms in the hands of the citizenry was considered a deterrent to the kinds of oppressive governments that they had first hand knowledge of (and still exist). They were also viewed in the light that everyone has a basic “God-given” right to be able to defend themselves, their family, and their country to the best means that they see fit. This was though of as “freedom” (gad, what a concept).<br>
<br>
